games = games.dropna(subset=["Name", "Release date", "Price"])

games["Release date"] = pd.to_datetime(games["Release date"], errors="coerce")
games = games.dropna(subset=["Release date"])

games["Year"] = games["Release date"].dt.year

games["Price"] = pd.to_numeric(games["Price"], errors="coerce")

games = games[(games["Price"] >= 0) & (games["Price"] <= 200)]

games["Total reviews"] = games["Positive"] + games["Negative"]

games = games[games["Total reviews"] > 0]  # remove games with no reviews

games["Score ratio"] = games["Positive"] / games["Total reviews"]
genre_scores = (
    games.groupby("Primary Genre")["User score"]
         .mean()
         .reset_index()
         .sort_values("User score", ascending=False)
)

fig, axes = plt.subplots(2, 2, figsize=(16, 12))

    data=filtered,
    x="Price",
    y="Score ratio",
    alpha=0.25,
    ax=axes[0, 0]

)

axes[0, 1].set_title("Price vs Review Score (Trend)")

valid_genres = genre_counts[genre_counts > 500].index

When examining average user ratings by genre, some genres consistently receive higher average scores than others. Genres such as RPG, Simulation, and Adventure tend to have higher average review scores, while more common genres like Action and Casual show wider variation in ratings. This suggests that although Action games are the most numerous on Steam, they do not necessarily receive the highest average ratings. Genres with fewer releases may appeal more strongly to specific audiences, leading to higher average review scores.

The scatter plot comparing price and user rating shows a large amount of overlap, indicating no strong relationship between price and rating at the individual game level. Many low-priced and free games receive both very high and very low ratings. However, the trend line suggests a weak positive relationship between price and average rating, meaning that more expensive games tend to have slightly higher review scores on average. This relationship is small and should not be interpreted as higher price causing higher ratings.

When looking at average review scores by release year, ratings fluctuate over time rather than following a clear upward or downward trend. Earlier years show more variability, likely due to fewer games being released, while more recent years appear more stable as the number of games increases. Overall, release year alone does not strongly determine how well a game is rated, suggesting that other factors such as genre and gameplay quality play a larger role.

This analysis has several limitations. User reviews on Steam may be biased, as players who feel strongly about a game are more likely to leave reviews. Additionally, some genres have far more games than others, which can affect average ratings. Price data is also discrete, leading to overlapping points in visualizations. Finally, this project focuses on exploratory analysis and does not attempt to control for other factors such as developer reputation or marketing, which may influence ratings.
